social_posts.post_text: after two + a half years, i guess i couldn’t avoid the vid any longer. i’ve been laid out since sunday evening, now feeling well enough to get out of bed. i had big plans for this week: finish a couple projects, launch a shop update, go visit our cabinet maker with paint (because our cabinetry is finished, squeal) but instead taking it as a sign to rest and take it slower than slow. a grateful heart for the friends who showed up nourishment. tucking back in for my winters rest…
december one | we stopped in our tracks as several cardinals fluttered, chasing each other along the driveway under the juniper tree. i caught one with my lens as snowflakes danced around him.

to be honest, things have felt off for me not being in our own home for the past few months. the familiar comforts not quite there. did i have a mini meltdown when aj brought home cool white holiday lights instead of our usual warm white when we couldn’t find our holiday box in storage…yes, yes i did. allowing myself the grace that this year can look + feel different if need be. yet i’m ever so grateful for @toast sharing a little holiday joy to reclaim my elfing spirit.
to decorate at the construction site or not to decorate, that is the question…and if i put up this wreath, will they make me take it down 🤪

with drywall wrapping up this week, here’s a sneak peek of our build color palette. stepping outside my comfort zone a bit to bring in color in some nooks + crannies. featured here @farrowandball new colors stirabout, bamboozle, templeton pink and classics treron + schoolhouse white. i can’t wait to show you what is going where!
slow december movements as we wake to snow globe days. grateful for natures winter offerings + honoring my body’s pace.

finding beauty + stillness in allowing this season to look + feel different than years gone by. part of the holidays that i find hard year after year is the sense of expectations that can overwhelm. i’ve been paying close attention to what deserves my energy + what i can release. as i reflect on this year gone by, and all i’ve given myself too, i’m allowing myself to be tired, to tend to the small moments + to call parts of me home, howling under the cold full moon.
nostalgia | getting in the mood for some winter baking, thinking spritz cookies + bourbon sea salt fudge. what are your favorite holiday baking recipes?

through my lens | shop update | between snow days + sick ones, i’ve fallen a bit behind. if you are signed up for my newsletter you might have seen but i am quite excited to share seasonal glimpses through my lens, in print, in the shop. i will be selecting a few captures per season, to offer in my shop in three sizes. printed sustainably with remarkable fine art quality for you to bring into your hearth + home. i’ll be adding one of these winter wonderland captures this afternoon, which one should i choose? ❄️ 🌲

as temperatures drop, cozying in for a few days before diving into the holiday rush. as the moon wanes towards new, i’m feeling the pull inward, to reflect on the year gone by, + what unknown waits ahead. taking these moments to myself feel like striving towards balance in a season of lights + glitter, how can we hold + make space for the darkness too?

letting gratitude in. our exterior lighting is up, but still attempting to decide on hardware for the door. any favorites?

happy holidays | one car stuck in a snow drift, a stack of holidays cards unsent, one batch of orange slices burnt, yet we made new memories belting out our favorite holiday songs while we hand delivered holiday cards + sugar cookies to friends around town. 

although celebrations look different than our usual ones, we have such happy hearts for the time spent together. we can look outside our usual ways to locate the spirit of love + connection threaded through this season. i set aside my self prescribed to do lists, too high expectations in exchange for simple gestures of kindness and love as a reminder “you are enough, this is more than enough”. 

wishing you + yours warmth, connection + ease as this year comes to a close.

watching sandhill cranes in flight + these words i’d crossed before flooded my heart…

“and we pray, not for new
earth or heaven, but to be quiet
in heart, and in eye clear.
what we need is here”

wendell berry

2022 | so much has happened this year. i haven’t quite found the words to wrap around the experience. all i know is as i went to compile this video i realized how much life, love + gratitude cannot fit into these squares. thank you so much for being here + i am beyond grateful for you. see you in twenty twenty three.

wolf moon | a blessed first full moon of the year rising over the driftless. as the sun sits in capricorn and this moon rises in cancer, my attention has turned to the intersection of work + home, a devotion to both. i’ve spending my days embodied, painting our home to ready it for the final stages of the build. capricorn reminds me of the structures, the bones, the foundations of what we build and who we are, and cancer the flesh, the waters, the softness;  what makes a house a home. under this lunation i’ve released a sense of stuckness + surrendering to a flow i thought was missing. how are you feeling under this cancer full moon?

friday 13th | on this venus day + waning libra moon i’ve been reflecting on how to lean back into the little rituals. the one that used to come so easily to me. the stolen moments, between work + rest + parenting, however small they are the ones that fill you with receptivity + softness and return my breath to my body. trying to find a balance between showing up for the necessary hard work + tending to the actions to fill my cup. what are you favorite way to sink in to yourself during the day to day grind?

calendula | we’ve got a month + a half left until we move into our new home. i’m so looking forward to pulling my herbs, oils, tinctures + concoctions out of storage and putting them onto my pantry shelves. working with the plants harvested from the late summer garden in the dead of winter is truly a light. 

i found, my relationship with plants comes from working with them daily. bringing them into my routines, and when i don’t or i can’t i feel a little lost. usually this time of year i’m mixing bath salts and making salves…

do you have an intimate relationship with plants? what’s on your list for winter making?

happy monday, friends.

“that’s what humans do: we make and remake our stories, abandoning the ones that no longer fit and trying on new ones for size | @katherinemay_ 

leaning into the energy of this snow moon to meet myself. to process the ups + downs, ins and outs of the past six months or more. to shed light on the stories in my mind, in my relationships, the ones that guide my ways of being. putting to rest the ones that no longer serve. here i sit to listen to the ghost of stories past with patience + compassion, so i can put them to rest. how can we show up more fully for ourselves + settle into our skins. so the growing light of the sun can awaken the seeds of new possibilities burst to the surface as i wait for spring.

full moons illuminate what lies in our darkness so we can see more clearly. i process the last lunar cycle, writing a list of what i am ready to release, sometimes burning it when i’m done (sometimes burning it up) + a separate list of gratitudes, readying my heart to receive. when i feel out of sorts, coming back to the moon + it’s cycles connect me to my place within time. remembering the sacred magic within the mundane.

“i just want to go home” | for days, i have been trying to wrap myself around these last words. now as we watch how homes, cities have crumbled around countless lives, i’m simultaneously pouring myself into the final stages building of our home. i’m so torn.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
i feel helpless at the inherent contradictions of this human experience. a part of me observes how i expand + contract in sync with events that feels so outside of my control. i wonder how can we truly show up for each other? how can i hold gratitude + grief? honor the suffering of others yet be present to the trinkets of our own joys. it feels wrong but what other choice do we have? tears roll down my cheeks as winter sun hits my face after its long absence.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
in the end it affirms what i know: we are all worth experiencing home, we are all worth love, we are all worth safety. period. in this season of love, i’m letting my heart break for our world. picking up the pieces in how i tend to what is within my reach.
as the snow melts, i’m giving into reveries of spring.

garden rêveries | this year we will be starting our garden from the ground up. our last home, the garden was formative + created by the owner before us, i added my touches and it changed shape over the years, but for the most part the foundation was there. i’m not quite sure what shape it will take, or where it will go but i’m feeling okay with taking my time to figure it out + excited all at once. 

i’ve been watching our current mud pit out the window, where the sun hits, where the snow is melting first, how the land curves, where water runs. i’m thinking a kitchen perennial herb + veggie garden right off the kitchen door where i can run out to snip a few herbs for dinner, and grab a few stalks of asparagus. with cut flower gardens behind that + a meandering wildflower prairie border between our garden + the woods.

the past few nights standing at the kitchen sink i’ve watched four or five deer passing behind the oak tree at dusk so i’m thinking the closer to the house the garden is the better. any suggestions for keeping deer friends out of the garden would be much appreciated. deer repelling plants? fencing?

thanks for listening to my garden daydreaming. as the snow melts, i’ll be heading outside to mark off the site for @shades_of_green_permaculture i’m excited to work with them to create a plan for our regenerative garden + to dive into their course regenerative backyard blueprint. i’ll be sharing more of the garden process on my journal.

a sunday well spent | i’ve been trying to find a balance between work + play, settling into our home in the country + staying connected with the folks we love. it’s been tricky to truly find the space to cherish the moments while juggling many hats. today felt just right.

deeply grateful for all the years i was given to stand under this crab apple tree as it blossomed. i realized recently that i will miss the spring joy this brought dancing outside our old kitchen window for the last five years. i’m glad i captured it, in all its glory + plotting where we might need to plant one in the future.
i took my morning cuppa of mushroom coffee on a sunrise walk to the edge of our woods. bloodroot blooms, the serenade of spring peepers + birdsong as the earth awakens.

elderflower lemonade | recipe below!

5-6 fresh elderflower heads, stems removed.
juice of one lemon
1/3 cup honey
4 cups of filtered, cold water
1 teaspoon apple cider vinegar 
1 lemon, washed and sliced

directions | mix all the ingredients including sliced lemons in a one liter jar. top with a lid. infuse for 4-6 hours, or overnight. strain and refrigerate. enjoy the lemonade over ice. today i’m enjoying topped with sparkling water. #myherbalstudies #botanicalpickmeup #seasonalfloweralliance #theartofslowliving #summerslowdown #mycountryliving

Hazelnut Chaga Bark 

chaga, a medicinal mushroom native to the northern regions of Europe, Asia, and North America and is used in spiritual practices bringing deep connection and harmony. like many medicinal mushrooms chaga is an Immuno-modulator meaning it regulates the immune system, bringing it into a state of balance. a wonderful support for this time of year when our systems are stressed and at risk. chaga contains antioxidant, anti-inflammatory properties and supports brain health promote cognitive function. share this chaga hazelnut bark as a gift or at your holiday gatherings. may your holiday goodies be good for you too!

INGREDIENTS
12 ounce package (about 2 cups) milk or dark chocolate chips
2 tablespoons chaga powder @animamundiherbals organically grown
4 ounces (about 1 cup) toasted and chopped hazelnuts
Maldon or a flaky sea salt, for garnish

DIRECTIONS

Spread hazelnuts on a baking sheet and toast for 10 minutes at 400°F. Let cool, then roughly chop and set aside.
Line a 9 x 13-inch pan with parchment paper.

Melt about ¾ of the chocolate and chaga (it doesn’t have to be exact) in a double boiler or medium heatproof bowl set over a pan of simmering water. Melt most of the chocolate together in the double boiler, removing the melted chocolate from the heat, then stirring in the remaining chocolate until completely melted. This simple, yet foolproof technique leads to beautifully tempered chocolate. No need to rely on thermometers.

Remove the bowl from the heat and stir in reserved chocolate chips until mixture is completely melted and smooth. Stir in half of the chopped hazelnuts.

Spread the chocolate and hazelnut mixture evenly into the prepared pan. Sprinkle with the reserved hazelnuts and flaky sea salt. Gently press the hazelnuts into the chocolate mixture so they adhere to the bark.

Refrigerate until the bark has set, about 1 hour, then break into pieces. Stored in an airtight container in a cool place or in the fridge.
